<paragraph id="8B8236C7FFD5FFFFFFEAFBBE6C40FB93" blockId="87.[151,1437,901,1683]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
The Quenstedt collection is probably stored in the Institut für Geowissenschaften of the Eberhard Karls Universität Tübingen but we have not been able to obtain pictures of the 
<typeStatus id="54868865FFD5FFFFFCE5FB926C5CFB93" box="[968,1070,1081,1107]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">syntypes</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8236C7FFD5FFFFFFEAFBF66D52FA8F" blockId="87.[151,1437,901,1683]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFFEAFBF669C8FBB7" bold="true" box="[199,442,1117,1143]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Revised description.</emphasis>
Shell medium-sized, solid, moderately slender fusiform; apical angle ~33°. Protoconch and early teleoconch not preserved. Subsutural collar moderately swollen, bearing indistinct tubercles. Suprasutural spiral cord with blunt tubercles, in some distance to deeply incised suture. Mid-whorl moderately concave, with delicate spiral cords and dense pattern of growth lines of anal sinus. Last whorl with tubercular shoulder cord, weakly convex below, weakly constricted at base. Sculpture of low, slightly opisthocline, rounded ribs developed below shoulder, crossed by irregular flattened cords, separated by narrow grooves, forming weakly beaded sculpture. Peribasal and perifasciolar cords somewhat strengthened with small, pointed nodes. Aperture unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C327654CFFD5FFFFFFEAFAF26A57F98B" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8236C7FFD5FFFFFFEAFAF26B66F9E7" blockId="87.[151,1437,901,1683]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFFEAFAF2693EFAB3" bold="true" box="[199,332,1369,1395]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D44FFD5FFFFFE75FAF26B45FAB3" authority="(Quenstedt, 1884)" baseAuthorityName="Quenstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[344,823,1369,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Phylloxeridae" genus="Olegia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="winterlingensis">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFE75FAF26A2EFAB3" box="[344,604,1369,1395]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Olegia winterlingensis</emphasis>
(Quenstedt, 1884)
</taxonomicName>
is a rather overlooked species, which has not been mentioned in the Paratethyan literature. The general shape and sculpture and especially the densely spaced growth lines along the anal sinus place this species in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D44FFD5FFFFFDB6FA0A6A95FA7B" authorityName="Harzhauser &amp; Landau &amp; Janssen" authorityYear="2022" box="[667,743,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Phylloxeridae" genus="Olegia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFDB6FA0A6A95FA7B" box="[667,743,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Olegia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D44FFD5FFFFFDD8FA0A6B80FA7B" baseAuthorityName="Quenstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[757,1010,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Phylloxeridae" genus="Olegia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="winterlingensis">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFDD8FA0A6B80FA7B" box="[757,1010,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Olegia winterlingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is strongly reminiscent of the roughly coeval 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D44FFD5FFFFFFC7FA6E6AACFA1F" authority="(Hoernes &amp; Auinger, 1891)" authorityName="Harzhauser &amp; Landau &amp; Janssen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[234,734,1477,1503]" class="Insecta" family="Phylloxeridae" genus="Olegia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agathae">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFFC7FA6E69E8FA1F" box="[234,410,1477,1503]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Olegia agathae</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAC4B36FFD5FFFFFE86FA6E6AA7FA1F" author="Hoernes, R. &amp; Auinger, M." box="[427,725,1477,1503]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" pagination="283 - 382" refId="ref135318" refString="Hoernes, R. &amp; Auinger, M. (1891) Die Gasteropoden der Meeres-Ablagerungen der ersten und zweiten Miocanen Mediterran- Stufe in der Osterreichisch-Ungarischen Monarchie. Abhandlungen der kaiserlich-koniglichen Geologischen Reichsanstalt, 12, 283 - 382, pls 37 - 50. [https: // opac. geologie. ac. at / ais 312 / dokumente / Hoernes % 20 und % 20 Auinger % 20 _ 1879 _ Gasteropoden. pdf]" type="journal article" year="1891">Hoernes &amp; Auinger, 1891</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Austrian Korneuburg Basin. The two species differ mainly by the pointed nodes on the subsutural collar and prominent tubercles on the shoulder of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D44FFD5FFFFFA38FA426DE7F9C3" authorityName="Harzhauser &amp; Landau &amp; Janssen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[1301,1429,1513,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Phylloxeridae" genus="Olegia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agathae">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFA38FA426DE7F9C3" box="[1301,1429,1513,1539]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">O. agathae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, the shoulder of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3D4D44FFD5FFFFFEECF9A66A4CF9E7" authorityName="Harzhauser &amp; Landau &amp; Janssen" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Hoernes &amp; Auinger" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[449,574,1549,1575]" class="Insecta" family="Phylloxeridae" genus="Olegia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agathae">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFEECF9A66A4CF9E7" box="[449,574,1549,1575]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">O. agathae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more angulated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8236C7FFD5FFFFFFEAF99A6A57F98B" blockId="87.[151,1437,901,1683]" box="[199,549,1585,1611]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFFEAF99A69DAF98B" bold="true" box="[199,424,1585,1611]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Paleoenvironment.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C327654CFFD5FFFFFFEAF9FE6A4CF953" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8236C7FFD5FFFFFFEAF9FE6A4CF953" blockId="87.[151,1437,901,1683]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis id="B949EAD5FFD5FFFFFFEAF9FE6A12F9AF" bold="true" box="[199,608,1621,1647]" pageId="87" pageNumber="88">Distribution in Central Paratethys.</emphasis>
Eggenburgian/Ottnangian (early Miocene): 
